In the second part of his wide-ranging conversation with Another Man, cult filmmaker, artist and spiritual provocateur @alejandro.jodorowsky reflects on the ecstatic chaos of making art, the psychic wounds of childhood, and the surreal chain of events that shaped his singular worldview.
Jodorowsky is a Chilean-born filmmaker, artist and writer whose work spans theatre, cinema, comics, poetry and tarot. After early experimental theatre in Chile and studies in Paris under Marcel Marceau, he emerged as a singular voice in surreal cinema with films like Fando y Lis, El Topo and The Holy Mountain. Now in his late nineties, he continues to create across disciplines, treating art as an ongoing, living process.
“I don’t create things. I receive things. I have received for almost 100 years. I had lost myself and through these images made rediscoveries. Rediscovery is a union of the brain, the heart and the sex,” he says. Read more on Substack at the link in bio.
Interview by @jackstuartmills
